I recently recorded a screencast [1], about linux cgroups, and how you can restrict/shape various program resources. For one of the examples, I wrote the following C program to take 50MB of memory, at around the 15:45 mark in the screencast you can see it in action, but this could easy be modified, and add a sleep, to hold the memory for a while. You would most likely need to disable swap if you wanted to use 90% of the free memory, run &quot;free -m; swapoff -a; free -m&quot; as root, then use &quot;swapon -a&quot; to enable it again.<p><pre><code>  #include <stdio.h>
  #include <stdlib.h>
  #include <string.h>

  int main(void) {

      int i;
      char *p;

      /* intro message */
      printf(&quot;Starting ...
&quot;);

      /* loop 50 times, try and consume 50 MB of memory */
      for (i = 0; i < 50; ++i) {

          /* failure to allocate memory? */
          if ((p = malloc(1<<20)) == NULL) {
              printf(&quot;Malloc failed at %d MB
&quot;, i);
              return 0;
          }

          /* take memory and tell user where we are at */
          memset(p, 0, (1<<20));
          printf(&quot;Allocated %d to %d MB
&quot;, i, i+1);

      }

      /* exit message and return */
      printf(&quot;Done!
&quot;);
      return 0;

  }
</code></pre>
[1] <a href="http://sysadmincasts.com/episodes/14-introduction-to-linux-control-groups-cgroups" rel="nofollow">http://sysadmincasts.com/episodes/14-introduction-to-linux-c...</a>

